  {
    "district":"District 01",
    "candidateName":"Scott Goldman",
    "candidateLastName":"Goldman",
    "photo":"goldman",
    "party":"Democrat",
    "dob":"10/19/1981",
    "age":34,
    "endorsed":"yes",
    "job":"U.S. Army Reservist",
    "livesIn":"Canton",
    "graduatedFrom":"I attended Harvard College and Vanderbilt University Law School.  My military training includes completing the Judge Advocate Officer Basic Course in Charlottesville, Virginia, and Basic Officer Leadership Course at Fort Benning, Georgia.  ",
    "website":"GoldmanForBaltimore.com",
    "twitter":"@GoldmanForBmore",
    "facebook":"facebook.com/goldmanforbaltimore",
    "bio":"<p>Goldman, an Army officer, has not previously held elected office. He is a graduate of Harvard College and Vanderbilt University Law School.</p>",
    "q1":"I'm campaigning for (1) safe neighborhoods, (2) strong schools, and (3) smart development strategies and property tax reform.</p><p>Safe Neighborhoods: I support the transition to a community-policing model to build trust between the police and community. From new schedules, to new training, to basic technology upgrades like putting computers in police vehicles, I will be an advocate on the Council for this new approach.</p><p>Strong Schools: I have a nine-month-old son who I hope one day will attend Baltimore City Schools. What I hear over and over again from teachers and principals in our schools is that they are succeeding despite the bureaucracy of North Avenue. I support oversight and reform to (1) create better incentives and training for teachers and principals; (2) making it the standard for schools to become \"Community Schools\"; and (3) keeping the 21st Century Schools Construction plan on track.</p><p>Smart Development and Property Tax Reform. We should maintain the exciting growth in Southeast Baltimore but do so in a smart way, planning ahead for how development impacts education, transportation, parking, and our green space. We also need to experiment with progressive tax reform – such as property tax penalties on vacant and blighted property – to lower our property taxes and reduce blight.</p>",
    "q2":"I believe that Baltimore's best days are ahead, and they will be achieved by rebuilding the trust between our police and residents. That starts with standardized patrol assignments and increased outreach from Baltimore Police Department (BPD) to citizens and businesses.</p><p>I support the current leadership in the BPD and Commissioner Davis's efforts to transition the culture of policing in the City from a \"warrior\" to a \"guardian\" approach. </p><p>As a former prosecutor and current community-policing advocate who is dedicated to building trust between the police and our neighborhoods, I know the Baltimore Police Department has systemic, structural problems to address. Too many officers patrolling the streets feel under siege and too many of our citizens do not trust the people sworn to protect them. If elected, I will ensure the City Council provides strong oversight of the BPD and ensure that we successfully transition to the community-policing model through partnership and communication with our neighborhoods.</p>",
    "q3":"Whether you call it the unrest, or the riots, or the uprising, I remember April 27, 2015, as the night my wife and I realized that we would not be able to get to a hospital when she was eight and a half months pregnant. The divisions, injustice, and disorder in our City led to the violence that night, and the first lesson I take from it was that we – as neighbors, community leaders, and proud Baltimoreans – have the responsibility to make sure it doesn't happen again. We have to reform our police tactics, address systemic poverty and racism, end lead poisoning, and face the historic cultural divides in our city.</p><p>I was – and I am – angry that a human being died in police custody in America in the twenty-first century. As a veteran, I'm proud to have served a country where people have the right to peacefully assemble to protest in a unified voice. As a former prosecutor, I believe all parties are entitled to a fair and impartial trial. As a community-policing advocate, I want to ensure we use this moment to reform our policing tactics and rebuild trust between our communities and the police. </p><p>Unfortunately, tragedies like this remind us all of the divide within our community between those who trust the police to protect and those who fear the motivations of all law enforcement. </p><p>Despite it all, as someone who still believes in progress, I'm hopeful for the future.</p>",
    "q4":"Baltimore needs progressive tax reform to lower our property taxes. Baltimore will never compete as a city for new residents and businesses when our taxes are twice as high as that of our neighbors. Baltimore, with the support of the State legislature, should pilot tiered tax rates for vacant property. Washington, D.C., for example, institutes a 5% property tax penalty on vacant property and a 10% penalty on blighted property. Other cities also tax land and improvements at different rates in order to incentivize turning over vacant property and reward improving one's property. Baltimore's needs more affordable housing and business property and also has a booming stock of vacant property. Experimenting with progressive property tax reform could unlock market forces to encourage redevelopment.</p><p>I support the limited use of payments in lieu of taxes (PILOTs) and tax increment financing (TIFs) as part of a smart development approach to encourage construction and renovation that would otherwise not occur in economically challenged parts of the City. But we need to leverage these incentives to bring more family-sustaining construction work, green space, and affordable housing through our agreements with developers. </p><p>Most importantly, the City's goal must be to lower property taxes for all, so that more families choose to move to Baltimore and stay here for a lifetime.</p>",
    "q5":"First, we have to make our City government more effective so that neighborhoods across this City enjoy a sense of progress and functionality that is now missing. Second, we should begin progressive tax reforms (discussed in my answer to question four) to reward property owners for maintaining their homes and discourage vacancy and blight. Third, we should continue the Vacants-to-Value program with targeted enforcement of challenged properties or areas. This program has had successes so far, but it could be even more transformative with effective tax reform. Fourth, and finally, I welcome the Governor's recent proposal of $700 million worth of demolition and development incentives, but I am concerned that his budget appears to simply repackage old programs rather than provide new money and ideas. It will be necessary for the City Council, the Mayor, and our State delegation to make sure this program is not just a paper promise.</p>",
    "q6":"The chief barrier to economic development and job creation in Baltimore is the dysfunctionality and bureaucracy of city government. I've met too many business owners in the First District who have said that if given the chance to do it over again, they would not start a business here. From inefficient permitting processes, to arbitrary enforcement against people and workers doing the right things, to the sense that only the well-connected can get anything done, these barriers are of our own creation. I believe when we govern right, economic growth will follow. </p><p>Our residents are our greatest resource and there is no government benefit that can compete with a family-supporting job. The City and State must leverage all of its available resources to ensure that every child receives a high-quality K-12 education. Moreover, we must work with our partners in Annapolis to ensure students receive a high-quality education at Baltimore City Community College and our local universities. And for the men and women seeking to make an investment in their future later in life, we need to ensure that continuing adult education, GED courses, and ESOL classes are accessible and affordable. </p><p>Finally, our transportation system is woefully inadequate to move Baltimoreans between the jobs they have now, let alone the jobs we hope to create in the future. The City Council and Mayor must work with our State delegation to improve and reform MTA service and ensure the Governor's B-Link program creates meaningful transit options for all residents.</p>",
    "q7":"A lesson I learned in the Army is that power and authority do not always line up. It is true that the City Council is structurally weak in comparison to the Mayor. I will seek to rebalance this relationship by giving the City Council a significant role in the budgeting process and reducing the veto override number from three-quarters of Council Members to two-thirds. But the focus on structural power in this debate misses the point that the Council has authority it does not use. Regardless of any structural changes in the Mayor-Council relationship, I plan to use my position on the Council to exercise oversight, bring critical issues to light, and build real partnerships with City agencies and personnel.</p>",
    "q8":"I applaud the City Council's important legislative achievements over the past four years, including expanding the Community Schools program, adopting new building codes to promote green construction, requiring more local hiring on publicly supported development projects, and requiring audits that will be essential to making our city government work again. </p><p>The next City Council has to take this work to the next level, making the Community Schools program the standard in Baltimore, adopting new approaches to smart development, and using the results of audits to streamline and improve city services.</p>",
    "q9":"Improving City services is the central goal of my campaign. If you talk with anyone who has lived in Baltimore for more than 50 years, they will tell you about a time when things just seemed to work – in contrast to what we have now. Baltimoreans don't expect the Mayor to drive around the City at 3:00 am every night, calling in potholes (a story people still tell about Mayor Schaefer). But we do expect a greater sense of urgency and progress in the problems we report.</p><p>We can't make progress in our City's challenges until we know where our residents' tax dollars are going. To make city government work again, I would start by completing the audits of city agencies and making audits routine for all agencies. We also need to change the culture in city government from one concerned with credit, blame, and political appearances to one driven by a desire to get things done. Baltimore 311 is also a remarkable system that could transform how the city functions. But how many times does a 311 ticket close without explanation or adequate investigation? Finally, we must continue to revive CitiStat, which has languished until recently. </p>",
    "q10":"Not long after I came home from Afghanistan in 2014, a city water pipe burst under the street in front of our house. I assumed that in America in the twenty-first century, I could call the City and someone would come fix it. Instead, I got three months of every kind of government dysfunction imaginable. Meanwhile, our basement flooded and the street cracked. </p><p>Compounded by the systemic challenges we face, from public education, to public justice, access to family-supporting jobs, disinvestment, blight, and historical cultural inequities, I realized that my experience with City Hall was only a symptom of a much larger problem. </p><p>With the support of my family, friends, and neighbors, I decided to run for City Council to tackle government dysfunction and work to make our communities safer and stronger for all families. </p><p>I will bring the skills, discipline, and temperament needed to get things done for the people of the First District. </p>"
  },
  {
    "district":"District 01",
    "candidateName":"Ed Marcinko",
    "candidateLastName":"Marcinko",
    "photo":"marcinko",
    "party":"Democrat",
    "dob":"2/20/1959",
    "age":57,
    "job":"Retired; 32 years in law enforcement as Special Agent, DEA, Drug Enforcement Administration, Dept of Justice, Baltimore District Office",
    "livesIn":"Upper Fells Point",
    "graduatedFrom":"BS Criminal Justice, University of Baltimore.",
    "website":"edmarcinko.com",
    "twitter":"@EdMarcinko2016",
    "facebook":"facebook.com/edward.marcinko",
    "bio":"<p>Marcinko, a retired DEA agent, has not previously held elected office. He was previously president of the Upper Fells Point Improvement Association. Marcinko has a bachelor’s degree in criminal justice from the University of Baltimore.</p>",
    "q1":"Development / Transportation: they both go hand in hand. We need smart development but not over development. We need to protect the Historic neighborhood of Fells Point and other areas from being overdeveloped. Buildings that are 60 to 100 ft in height do not belong in a historic, 250yr old neighborhood, which is currently planned in the new Transform Baltimore zoning regulations. I watched how my parents protested in the 1960's to save Fells Point from the dreaded highway; we need proper infrastructure before we continue with major developments. There are too many vehicles in Fells Point and not enough friendly bike lanes and walk lanes that were suggested in the Fells Point Master plan. </p><p>School Improvement: we need more city and state budget funding to go towards city schools and more accountability from North Ave, HQ. In the 1st district, Wolfe Academy, I consider it a model school. The school is a converted charter school which is unique in itself. The population of the school is about 90% minority but the school is ranked 2nd in academic just behind the Roland Park school. Community groups, residents and businesses work hand in hand with this school to make this school a better school. </p><p>City Services: while the 311 system works well, it works well with minor issues. With major issues we need more accountability and supervision. . Crime/Safety issues; more community policing is needed and support of small businesses by reducing the minor privilege tax burden.</p>",
    "q2":"Yes... Baltimore is pursuing the right strategies. I have total confidence with the new police commissioner. We need more community policing and more in-service training. We need to identify mental health issues when individuals are involved with the police. The LEAD program I believe will work well in Baltimore as it has done so in Seattle with respect to non-violent offenders. Zero tolerance is not the answer; identification of mental health issues along with both drug and alcohol addiction is a key factor in today's law enforcement strategy. We need aggressive police work when it comes to violent offenders and with repeat offenders. Operation Cease Fire is a good program when the city and federal agencies are involved but it must be an on-going program. Drug Trafficking Organizations, DTO'S should also be aggressively targeted along with gun violence. Law enforcement alone can not solve the city crime problems. We need a holistic approach to improve our city; from better housing, schools, job training and better transportation to help all citizens. We either invest now in education and after school activities and rec centers or pay later with incarceration.</p>",
    "q3":"We have a huge economic disparity problem in this city. Decades have gone by with little to no help in addressing this problem in certain areas in the city. That's why we need all elected officials to work full time for their constituents, we don't need part time politicians. We need a holistic approach to improve our city; from better housing, schools, job training and better transportation to help all citizens. We need to encourage development in other parts of the city. The police need better and constant in-service training. I agree with home tax credit to entice more police to live in the city. I spent 32 yrs in law enforcement and I live in the city. I respect civil protest but when the protest becomes violent or if laws are broken and people get hurt or property destroyed, the police need to step in and enforce the law. For drug issues we need, treatment programs, we need education, prevention training and enforcement of the most violent offenders.</p>",
    "q4":"Yes...we need to do our best to reduce our tax rate. In the city, speculators own block after block in certain areas of the city and their property tax is very minimal. The vacant property sits year after year with speculators doing nothing to improve the block. We need to charge these owners more; we need to increase the land fee more than the building fee for these properties. Speculators are hurting the city with their blighted blocks, vacant homes and vacant land that they own; they need to pay more than homeowners. Completion of our Audit system, audits need to be completed, waste and abuse of city funds must end. From DPW to our school system there is too much waste of tax dollars and only with proper audits will we see how our money is spent. </p><p>TIF's and payments in lieu of taxes etc must be monitored very strictly. In certain blighted areas of the city where development is really needed, yes we should entertain these kinds of benefits. We need to encourage smart development; development that will help other areas of the city. By encouraging proper development, jobs will be created and communities will prosper. Our city tax based grew over 2 billion dollars because of development, but its an \"artificial wealth\". We need to stop tax deals (TIF's etc) from affecting our education fund that we receive from the State, until projects begin paying property tax into the general fund.</p>",
    "q5":"Tax incentives in these areas will help build a better Baltimore. We need to invest in other areas of the city, not just along the water front areas. We need to modify the minor privilege tax program so that people will invest in small businesses in the city. Small businesses are the backbone of the city. Transportation and infrastructure improvement is a must. We need these improvements so that people can walk to work, take a bus to work and be able to shop and buy local. Food deserts in areas are unacceptable. We need to concentrate on blighted areas of the city. Gov Hogan's plan is a start, but we need more assistance from the State. Baltimore city is the economic engine of the State. With the improvement of Baltimore, we will greatly improve our State overall.</p>",
    "q6":"Lack of proper Transportation: folks need to be able to go back and forth to work in a timely fashion. Our current bus routes are outdated; they go no where. We need bus routes to go where people live to where they work in a timely fashion. </p><p>The cost of doing business in Baltimore is expensive with our excessive taxes we put on businesses. We need to do everything we can to encourage job creation. To start a small business, it takes lots of work and capital expense to get up and running. Reducing the business tax burden will hopefully encourage more businesses to open, thus jobs will be created and more supplies, etc will be purchase and what's lost in minor privilege tax will be offset with other taxes generated by the business. Crime/Safety issues: when people and businesses feel safe more money is then spent in the city. More community policing and foot patrol will bring communities and police together. </p><p>Job training for residents: we need a way to generate a good job training base; educate folks in the proper way of resume writing, interview techniques and the proper way to dress and to speak properly to potential employers. In doing the above, residents will feel better about themselves and have hope. Folks have to have hope that things will get better.</p>",
    "q7":"Changes need to be made. To over ride the mayor now by veto we need 3/4 votes by city council. We need to change the vote from 3/4 to 2/3 vote. The City Council needs to be more involved in the Mayors budget plan. I believe that a line item veto for city council should be studied. The Board of Estimate, BOE also needs to be modified. The mayor has too much power at the BOE. Instead of 5 member there should be only 3 members; Mayor, Council President and Comptroller. To do all this either we need to vote in legislation changes or by a voters referendum.</p>",
    "q8":"We need all our city council members to work full time for their constituents and for the city. Committee bills and legislation bills are constantly stuck in committees because our council folks don't show up for work; the bills die in committee. The council salary is a full time salary; we need to demand that our council person work full time.</p><p>We need education reform, more transparency with how North Ave spends money: We need to focus on Economic disparity in areas of the city and improve these areas. Crime issues are always important, we can not arrest ourselves out of this situation, we need treatment for addiction and for metal illness. Youth programs are desperately needed, we need recreation centers which include after school activities. Again, we need to invest in our children now at a young age, we either pay now for better education or pay later with incarceration.</p>",
    "q9":"The 311 system works fine with minor issues, but with major issues the process lacks accountability and proper supervision. If a complaint is forward to the wrong dept, that dept closes the ticket and nother more is done. The caller has to call again for the same complaint. Many times tickets are closed but the problem is still outstanding because there is no supervision to see if the complaint was handled correctly. We spend more money (tax money) in going back and forth with issues instead of handling the complaint the correct way the first time its reported...make it right the first time, saves money. A full time elected officials needs to stay active in the community; constituents services comes first, that is why our council members need to be full time council members.</p>",
    "q10":"I spent 32 yrs as a Public Servant helping people and many years as a community leader and community activist serving my community. As a community leader, I developed the pilot program for community alley gating. This program helps communities regain yard areas and provides a safe play area for families and children. I want to continue to be a public servant but I want to take it to the next level and be a full time public servant, not a part-time politician. All city elected officials should work full time, the salary is a full time salary so we should work for our constituents full time. I was born and raised in the 1st District, knowing the issues in the district like I do is priceless. I worked to develop a city own blighted building in which the city would not do anything but let the building decay. I found a local developer to invest in this building and turn this city own property into an affordable senior living complex. Subsequently, developers saw the success of this project and other near by run down buildings in the area were rehabbed and are now generating income for the city, the buildings are now paying market rate property tax. I was a team member in which the community recently shut down The Big Easy strip club in Fells Point. We worked very hard for over 2 yrs to shut this businesses down. Team work and working together is a huge part of my campaign message.</p>"
  },
  {
    "district":"District 01",
    "candidateName":"Matthew McDaniel",
    "candidateLastName":"McDaniel",
    "photo":"matthew-mcdaniel",
    "party":"Republican",
    "dob":"6/14/1988",
    "age":27,
    "endorsed":"yes",
    "job":"Attorney",
    "livesIn":"Canton",
    "graduatedFrom":"I graduated from Loyola University in Maryland in 2010 with a Bachelor's Degree in History and Political Science. I received my law degree from the University of Baltimore in 2013 and was admitted to the Bar in 2013.",
    "website":"ChooseMatt.com",
    "twitter":"@McD4District1",
    "facebook":"facebook.com/McDanielForDistrictOne",
    "bio":"<p>McDaniel, a lawyer, has not previously held elected office. He received his law degree from the University of Baltimore.</p>",
    "q1":"The concerns of First District residents are similar to those of people around the City: crime, taxes, and politicians who don't seem to listen or care. </p><p>Crime has spiked in the Southeast and we need to address how criminals are entering our community and why. Commanders in the Southeast have noted that public-private cooperation to monitor the routes used by offenders is key to a long-term crime fighting strategy as well as deploying our diminished police resources to proactively combat criminal behavior.</p><p>Baltimore will be nearly bankrupt within a decade. We must grow the population in order to grow the tax base or else suffer the consequences of our decades of reckless spending. We must reduce both the property tax rate and the personal property tax rates significantly (and 50% for the first two years of home ownership). We should also work to reduce property taxes in a formula commensurate with population growth.</p><p>We need immediate and continuous audits of all City agencies and programs getting over $1M of taxpayer money. From schools to police and everything in between, there is a trust deficit in Baltimore. Until our City can show that its leaders can be effective stewards of citizens' hard-earned money, the books need to be opened and corruption must be rooted out. No new spending should be authorized unless a provision is incorporated that requires comprehensive and continuous audits and oversight of how any money is used.</p>",
    "q2":"I have confidence that the vast majority of Baltimore's Police Officers and members of the Sheriff's Department are doing everything in their power to make our community safe. I have confidence in the Commissioner and want to give him the resources that he and his commanders need to effectively secure the City.</p><p>Baltimore must be a leader in the national dialogue about policing. The failed war on drugs has led to mass incarcerations and distrust between police and the communities they serve. This problem has been decades in the making and cannot be fixed overnight. Smart economics is the ultimate solution to crime: a person with a 9-5 will not be motivated to stay up until 4am selling drugs. The \"demand side\" solutions to crime (treating addiction as a public health concern, making it less-profitable to sell drugs than to get an honest job, and providing housing and business ownership opportunities) are the future. Baltimore should be a leader in this regard.</p><p>A long-term plan notwithstanding, Baltimore is still reeling from its most violent year (per capita) on record. Police must work with the State's Attorney's Office, as well as federal law enforcement, to identify the most violent actors and the ringleaders of Baltimore's most dangerous organizations. </p><p>In the Southeast, officers and commanders have suggested that targeting resources towards cutting off the way criminals enter and move through the First District is smart policing that could immediately do good for residents.</p>",
    "q3":"Baltimore's struggles were laid bare to the nation last year. We must not withdraw from the spotlight, but rather become a national example of turnaround and recovery.</p><p>We all know that the unrest following Freddie Gray's death wasn't a week, or a month, or even a year in the making. Decades of economic decline, unkept promises, mass incarceration, and generations left behind created the powder keg that sat waiting for the match. As much as it pained us to watch national media covering riots in the streets, it was almost more upsetting to see the lack of coverage when people from across the City (far more than the group who created the unrest) came together to clean up.</p><p>The same neighborhoods that were on fire in 1968 burned again in 2016. It is unforgivable that, in fifty years, the economic and social concerns of our City's residents have been ignored in favor of a machine that has left them behind.</p><p>The lesson I draw from the death of Freddie Gray is that we must encourage ownership in Baltimore. The best way to turn our City around is to help people climb the economic ladder and pass on prosperity to their children instead of a sense of longing and despair.</p>",
    "q4":"Property taxes must be lowered in Baltimore. The fact that residents and business owners are paying more-than-double their counterparts anywhere else in the State is an absurdity. Growth in Baltimore is stagnant and, in order to offset a significant financial downturn approaching bankruptcy within the decade, Baltimore needs more residents. The only way to get people to come here in the short term is to make the City more affordable (if we weren't on the verge of insolvency, we would also want to expand services, but any expansion at this point would accelerate the decline). </p><p>An immediate and significant cut, halving the property tax for the first two years of ownership, slashing rates for small businesses and startups, and cutting rates commensurate with growth going forward are the ways we can grow Baltimore and avoid a financial catastrophe.</p><p>Development is essential to bring businesses to Baltimore. However, \"development for development's sake\" isn't what Baltimore needs. A prime example of this is a proposed historic overlay for Fells Point currently being met with resistance by the current City Council. Essentially, the overlay would create a building height restriction in historic Fells. The fact that we need this restriction shows the fear that residents have that development for the sake of development would not preserve the historic quality of our communities. We must undertake to revitalize and encourage businesses while also understanding the uniqueness of Baltimore's neighborhoods.</p>",
    "q5":"When I worked for the Office of the State's Attorney in the Sexual Assault and Domestic Violence Unit, I had the sad occasion to visit the scenes of where some of the most violent and disturbing crimes in our City were taking place: vacant homes. Not only are these sites of drugs, crime, prostitution, human trafficking, and violence, but they are also places where human tragedy goes unseen and unreported. </p><p>I fully support the Governor's effort to reduce blight in our City and I commend the Mayor for her efforts to accelerate removal of vacant houses.This is a bipartisan issue where we all are committed to making the City a better place for all of its residents.</p><p>With regard to revitalization of neighborhoods, we need to make Baltimore more affordable. Large property tax reductions for individual home buyers as well as encouragement for businesses to bring jobs into the City will help to transform communities.</p>",
    "q6":"The chief barrier to economic development in our City is City government. Businesses want to come to Baltimore and people want to live here. However, when they realize the cost of Baltimore and what they get in exchange for such a high rate, they look elsewhere. </p><p>Lowering property taxes, especially for new home buyers, is a critical first step to growing the tax base in the City. As much as we would want to immediately spend more on the myriad of \"quality of life\" issues that our City has, there is a looming budgetary shortfall that will be catastrophic for the City within the decade. It is critical that we get more people in the City and balance our financial outlook before we decide it's time to spend more on programs. </p><p>When the City is taxing small businesses more-than-double anywhere else in the State, is it any wonder that we are losing out on millions of dollars of venture spending despite having some of the best medical and technological infrastructure in the country. Baltimore must emulate other tech-focused cities and make starting a business in Baltimore easier. We need to realize that these businesses are not just \"white coat\" jobs, but also can provide countless, salaried, jobs to Baltimoreans looking for work. Coupled with on-the-job-training and health benefits, these are the kinds of jobs that can help someone buy their first home or eventually start a business of their own.</p>",
    "q7":"How can there be a balance of power without transparency? The balance between the Mayor and Council is less important than the balance between the politicians and the people. It is outrageous that audits are no completed while the City hurtles headlong towards default. Decades of failed policies have led to a situation where City Schools can report operating losses in the tens-of-millions of dollars and yet no bureaucrats are fired.</p><p>People are looking for voices outside of \"business as usual.\" I think people get into politics at the local level for many noble reasons. However, as we've seen consistently played out in both the Mayor's Office and City Council, having a full-slate of single-viewpoints leads to no oversight. </p><p>Even just one voice calling the system to account on behalf of the taxpayers and residents of the City would be an improvement over the status quo.</p>",
    "q8":"The City Council's primary role should be the growth and preservation of Baltimore. The Council must be both the steward of the City's finances and the overseer of the City's expenditures. The Council's role is to maintain transparency in government and make sure that members' constituents' voices are heard at City Hall.</p><p>The most important issue that comes before the Council each year is the City's budget. While the Council does not have full control over budgetary amendment, it is within the Council's purview to question and demand accountability on the spending of taxpayer money. Unfortunately, for decades, the Council has generally failed in this responsibility.</p><p>The Council's numerous votes on allowing for property tax reductions to bring businesses into Baltimore have been important, yet controversial, stepping stones towards growth. The unfortunate consequence of these tax breaks has been, as we are seeing this year, a mis- assessment in the State's education funding formula that calculates total taxable income in local jurisdictions in the allocation of State aid. Baltimore's legislators were right to try to bring businesses to Baltimore, but needed to think of the consequences of those actions. A simple change to the State's education budget formula (likely to be well-received since a stronger business climate in Baltimore is good for the region) could have saved millions.</p>",
    "q9":"We are all painfully aware after the heavy snowfall this winter that the City is often painfully reactive to problems instead of proactive.</p><p>One major example of this is the crumbling urban infrastructure. For decades, we have taken few steps to expand and modernize roads and water/wastewater distribution. Now, we have to deal with exorbitantly high water bills (some so high that residents are being foreclosed on because they cannot afford to pay), water-main bursts, sewage leakages, and crippling traffic. Let's be clear: these problems are the result of decades of inaction and inattention. </p><p>While the delivery of services, water issues, and congestion cannot be fixed overnight, we can take steps to encourage modernization, preventative maintenance, and the coordination with regional partners to allow for innovation and cooperation between jurisdictions for coordination of projects.</p><p>These issues are where residents are better suited than government to pinpoint where services are lacking. Rather than a top-down approach or a one-size-fits-all route to services, we need to listen to what our communities need and work to meet and surpass expectations. Through modernization and the cutting of waste and fraud, we should expect to see an increase in efficiency and responsiveness of City services.</p>",
    "q10":"I am running for office because Baltimore City is verging on insolvency within the decade. Lowering taxes, initiating audits, and providing transparency while opening up bipartisan dialogue are the keys to my message. Our City's economy must improve in order for our communities to thrive. As a property owner and an outsider to Baltimore's political machine, I am ready to bring accountability to our City's leadership.</p>"
  },
  {
    "district":"District 01",
    "candidateName":"Mark Parker",
    "candidateLastName":"Parker",
    "photo":"parker",
    "party":"Democrat",
    "dob":"3/3/1982",
    "age":33,
    "job":"Pastor, Breath of God Lutheran Church.",
    "livesIn":"Baltimore Highlands",
    "graduatedFrom":"St. Paul's School (2000) University of Maryland (2004): B.A. History, B.A. Government & Politics. Citations: Spanish & Neighborhood Revitalization. The Lutheran Theological Seminary at Philadelphia (2007): Master of Divinity",
    "website":"FriendsOfMarkParker.com",
    "twitter":"@1stDistrictMark",
    "facebook":"facebook.com/1stDistrictMark",
    "bio":"<p>Parker, a pastor, has not previously held elected office. He holds two bachelor's degree from the University of Maryland, College Park and a master's of divinity from the Lutheran Theological Seminary at Philadelphia.</p>",
    "q1":"Transportation is the most pressing issue in Southeast Baltimore. The population continues to expand, development abounds, while our streets stay the same size. There's no upside to a car-first transportation policy here. An east-west rail route is critical as the main artery of our transit system, and planning for that needs to begin now in anticipation of a more supportive state government. In the meantime, we can use city resources to invest in \"complete streets\" which make walking & biking safe and supported options for our dense historic neighborhoods. While the MTA is historically unresponsive and slow to change, I'm hopeful that we'll see significant improvement in bus reliability and capacity.</p><p>Southeast Baltimore schools have made great strides, but the success is uneven and the buildings can't handle the number of students we have here. I will push to expand funding for Community Schools, pressure North Avenue to be genuinely committed to parental and community engagement in the 21st Century Schools construction process, and advocate for increased ESOL staff serving our immigrant and refugee students. Long-term overcrowding can only be addressed by opening a new elementary-middle school.</p><p>Southeast Baltimore has historically been a place where immigrant communities could settle, buy homes, start businesses, build synagogues and churches, and create community. Our Latin American residents are central to our growth as a diverse, family-oriented community. They need to be well-served by the city and by their councilperson. We need better paths to homeownership and housing stability for these families to prosper.</p>",
    "q2":"The first question is premature. We are only nine months into Commissioner Davis' command. We've experienced the most violent year in our history. And we'll soon have a new mayor with a new approach. The past year hasn't been about implementing new policing strategies, it's been about trying somehow to stem the wave of violence while restoring departmental capacity and working to rebuild community trust.</p><p>We have made progress. Retention and morale have improved, new officers are being trained and entering service, and there is increased confidence by residents and officers in the leadership of Commissioner Davis.</p><p>Violent crime has root causes in addiction, drug trafficking, poverty, unequal opportunity, structural racism, family dysfunction, and our education system. The long-term path toward reduced--not just restrained--violent crime is largely outside the purview of the police.</p><p>For as necessary as it is to emphasize community policing strategies and focus on repeat violent offenders, there is no way to police ourselves out of our violence. Changes in drug policy that would take the profit motivation away from street-level dealing. Increased access to addiction treatment is necessary, as is the improvement of programs focused on young people: job training, education, recreation, youth employment, and mentoring.</p><p>Improved police-community relations begins with officers walking a beat and prioritizing relationship-building. Anti-racism, cultural competency, and deescalation techniques need to be taught at the academy and through in-service training. Financial incentives to attract first responders to become city homeowners will help. And the full roll-out of body cameras is critical.</p>",
    "q3":"Our city has undoubtedly improved over the past twenty years. We are no longer hemorrhaging thousands of people annually. Until 2015, our crime rate had been relatively stable and significantly lower than during the 1990s. Our schools have seen uneven progress but there are more high-quality schools and more flexibility for parents than in the recent past. Many neighborhoods which were at risk of decline have stabilized and begun to improve. While urban blight still dominates in many areas, there are real signs of growth, life, and improvement across many parts of the city.</p><p>The primary lesson I draw from the death of Freddie Gray in police custody, and the subsequent protests and unrest, is that we still have a long way to go. Whatever progress we have made has not improved conditions in many neighborhoods or changed circumstances for many people. When only 10% of our students who start high school will have a bachelors or associates degree ten years later... we have a long way to go. When 37% of black men aged 20-24 are unemployed... we have a long way to go. When 344 people are killed in one year, and more than 900 people are shot... we have a long way to go.</p><p>My hope is that the status quo has been so disrupted by the events of 2015 that our new mayor and City Council will be able to address our long-standing challenges with energy, creativity, and a political will which is currently lacking.</p>",
    "q4":"Yes, Baltimore should lower its property tax rate. The only way to lower our rate in a sustainable and responsible way is to drop it in small increments each year. Our tax base is expanding steadily at this time. This expansion, coupled with more efficient government operations, allows us to be able to afford small annual tax decreases while still maintaining city services. More aggressive proposals floated by fringe policy wonks or attention-seeking candidates are filled with dubious math and reckless economic assumptions. Other proposals seek to \"lower\" the tax rate by creating new fees or increasing existing fees--the idea of charging residents for trash disposal is a prime example. In such situations, we haven't really cut taxes--all we've done is moved our tax policy in a more regressive direction by charging flat fees instead of a progressive property or income tax.</p><p>TIFs and PILOTs have been used too freely over the past decade to subsidize development on some of the most expensive and profitable pieces of property in Baltimore City. There is a broad consensus among city residents that we cannot afford these kinds of policies any longer in light of deep needs elsewhere. I'm heartened to see some of these tax instruments being deployed in transitional neighborhoods away from the waterfront. When we do use these tools, a true community benefit has to result. Leveraging a TIF for a recreation center is nice--but getting guarantees of local hiring, job training, and living wages is more important.</p>",
    "q5":"The Main Streets program is an underutilized tool for encouraging neighborhood-level commercial revitalization. I've worked closely with the Highlandtown Main Streets program and know their effectiveness. I'm supportive of the city's efforts to renew the old manufacturing and warehouse areas along Broening Highway. Jobs in those factories sustained generations of Baltimore families, and increased employment opportunities beyond the normal service sector & retail offerings is important.</p><p>It's often the non-profit sector, in partnership with the government, which is able to make the most progress in terms of residential revitalization. I've worked with Habitat for Humanity, the Southeast Community Development Corporation, and the former Patterson Park Community Development Corporation. They are able to leverage private and public funds to repair homes, increase homeownership, and build community strength in transitional neighborhoods. The Baltimore Regional Neighborhood Initiative, championed by Delegate Hammen, has been successful and deserves further support. Community Land Trusts in other cities have stabilized and restored neighborhoods while prioritizing local leadership and maintaining permanent, affordable, community-controlled housing. CLTs need more policy and financial support from the city and our foundation community.</p><p>Vacants to Value is not perfect but has been the most successful of the three vacancy initiatives of the past fifteen years. We can work to improve it and make it more accessible for individual citizens. Any money that Governor Hogan wants to invest in Baltimore is a good thing--but knocking down buildings while simultaneously taking money out of our city schools and defunding the Red Line is nonsensical.</p>",
    "q6":"The chief barrier to economic development and job creation in Baltimore is an unprepared workforce. When only 10% of our high school students to on to earn any sort of college degree, and there are few real opportunities for job training and apprenticeship, we are left with high percentages of working-age residents who lack the education and skills for the family-supporting jobs that do exist. We need to emphasize vocational education within our high schools, create and expand adult job training centers in the city, work closely with unions and others who have the expertise and experience to run effective apprenticeship programs, and make sure that publicly-funded construction projects are committed to local hiring and job training.</p><p>High rates of addiction also makes a significant percentage of working-age adults functionally unemployable. This is an economic and a public health crisis. Expanded drug treatment and counseling is necessary to help bring people back into the workforce.</p><p>Taxes certainly are a barrier to economic development, and I already discussed my commitment to a slow but steady decrease in our property tax rate.</p>",
    "q7":"Our city has too many strong leaders, and too many challenges, for us to be able to afford to give the mayor as much power as the office currently holds. By rebalancing the systems of power in city government we can create a more collaborative governance model in which the City Council has a more significant role in setting the agenda and developing solutions. It is to a certain extent a waste of the council's time to sit around waiting for the mayor to send an idea their way for approval or rejection--and yet to often that seems to be the dynamic.</p><p>Specifically: 1) the Board of Estimates should have three members (Mayor, Council President, Comptroller). 2) There should be a 2/3rds threshold to override the mayor's veto. 3) The council should be given the authority to add, remove, and adjust line items in the budget.</p>",
    "q8":"There are so many challenges in our city that it is impossible to address all of them at once. Certainly the City Council (within the limits of its present authority) has been engaged in substantive work on police body cameras, recreation center funding, comprehensive rezoning, agency financial & performance audits, funding for youth initiatives, the stormwater fee implementation, and the charter changes regarding rebalancing mayoral and council power.</p><p>At the same time, the council seems to have given little attention to key issues around education, violent crime, police-community relations, housing policy (particularly the crisis in our housing department), and wide-spread efforts at improving employment and economic development.</p>",
    "q9":"The most widespread complaints in recent years have had to do with our water and sewer systems. Long-term maintenance has been put off for so long that there are major and minor crises around the city and throughout the year. Last spring it was possible to walk around Southeast Baltimore and see a water line break every block or two. Meanwhile, our failure to comply with the terms of the consent decree related to improving our sewer system is inexcusable. Every major storm seems to still overwhelm our system and cause us to pump raw sewage directly into our waterways. And of course our water and sewer rates have increased rapidly without a corresponding improvement in service.</p><p>The Department of Transportation is frustrating as well. They routinely fail to plan for the investments necessary to match the pace of development. The streets around Canton Crossing have still not been completed and improved in order to fully accommodate the traffic flow there. The Central Avenue bridge between Harbor East and Harbor Point won't be finished for more than a year after Exelon opens their offices there, routing all traffic onto Caroline Street. When road improvements are made, our lack of a \"one dig\" policy means that very often the same street will be torn up by BGE, repaired, and then torn up again by DOT.</p><p>Improved response time and resident satisfaction can be achieved through regular comprehensive audits, changes in agency leadership, and a greater commitment to communication and neighborhood outreach.</p>",
    "q10":"I am running for City Council because at this critical moment in the history of our city we need public servants who have a love for the people of Baltimore, who are deeply rooted in community, who are dedicated to collaborative leadership, who are optimistic about the future of our city, and who are realistic about the challenges we face. I strive every day to be that kind of leader, to put my own gifts and ideas and energy into the mix alongside community association members, teachers, community organizers, artists, non-profit staff members, business owners, and elected officials. We are all in this together, and I have been engaged in collaborative leadership for more than six years here in Southeast Baltimore--whether it's been an effort to welcome immigrants and refugees or a collaboration to build community across barriers of age and race, whether we're pushing to increase youth employment or remove persistent drug dealers from our corners, whether it's looking for ways to promote homeownership or create a new early childhood education center, whether it's addressing school overcrowding or serving on the master plan team for Patterson Park. In all of those efforts and more I have worked alongside talented and determined neighbors to make real change in our communities.</p><p>That's the kind of leadership we need on the City Council--someone willing to walk alongside other community leaders and be part of the collective long-term efforts necessary to address the major problems facing our district and our city.</p>"
  }
