    "bio":"<p>Tarrant served two terms in the House of Delegates, from 2007 to 2014. He has a bachelor's degree in finance and marketing from Norfolk State University.</p>",
    "q1":"Most pressing issue are Jobs, quality affordable housing, crime, blight and over development. I plan to address these issues by working closely with the residents of the 7th District along with City agencies, Police department and developers. There are solutions that involve working with many of the above mentioned stakeholders that solve more than one problem, Require developers before receiving a TIF to hire locally and have apprenticeship skill labor positions. This plan will bring higher income jobs so residents can afford better housing and bring down crime.</p>",
    "q2":"No, Baltimore is not doing what we need to do to reduce violent crimes. Yes, I have confidence in the new leadership. To improve police community relations I would organize meetings with district leaders and officers that patrol our community in the 7th district.</p>",
    "q3":"The lessons learned in my opinion where always there just not amplified until the Civil Unrest. We need to fight harder to give opportunities to those in all parts of the city, People should not be treated differently by our tax supported police force because of their neighborhood history of poverty and crime. Black Lives Matter more now than ever before.</p>",
    "q4":"Yes, I will support lowering the property tax rate to give people a relief and attract new residents. Tax incentives for developers should only be used when there are written agreements in place to hire local residents and dollars are set aside to uplift the community where development is being placed.</p>",
    "q5":"We can make it easier for small business owners to acquire properties to use for business purposes,. In the 7th District I have a plan to attract businesses to the North Avenue corridor with the Anchors of MICA and Coppin State University. Our communities in West Baltimore already have a commercial district but is vacant with no hopes of attracting new businesses. We must Improve the retail and housing and people will come and crime will drop. The program vacants to value has good intentions but has been slow going. Governor Hogan's plan can only work if we tear down the right properties and build new affordable housing in Baltimore and not just future problems with vacant lots.</p>",
    "q6":"Economic Development can only happen when city agencies perform at high levels to be a resource and not a barrier to development. I would address this issue by supporting the Mayor and Council with resources to a make Baltimore a business friendly City, Jobs that are created from these future projects must have living wages and apprenticeship programs. Once a person has a skilled profession he or she can provide for their family and support the tax base. The positive impact on a community will keep people employed with a Building Trade skill for llife</p>",
