  {
    "district":"District 07",
    "candidateName":"Westley West",
    "candidateLastName":"West",
    "photo":"west",
    "party":"Democrat",
    "dob":"4/8/1988",
    "age":27,
    "job":"Pastor of Faith Empowered Ministries, INC. (FEMINC)",
    "livesIn":"Coppin Heights/Ash-Co_East",
    "graduatedFrom":"Digital Harbor Alternative Learning Center ",
    "website":"westleywestbaltimore.org",
    "twitter":"@electPastorWest",
    "facebook":"facebook.com/westley.west.501",
    "bio":"<p>West, a pastor, has not previously held elected office. He was recently acquitted of charges stemming from a protest outside a court hearing for the officers charged in the Freddie Gray case.</p>",
    "q1":"I am running for office because I grew up, reside, and worship in West Baltimore. As a child I witnessed gun violence, people living in poverty, and the lack of opportunities in the communities that I grew up in and around. Unfortunately, more than 20 years later as an adult, I am still witnessing the same issues, but now, I am able to do something about it. I am able to connect with the youth, give a voice to those who are voiceless, and restore pride to my community that the elderly can be proud of again. West Baltimore is a beautiful place but there is some dust on it, as Councilman, I will brush the dust off and get to work as the bridge between Sandtown and City Hall, the bridge between Druid Park and City Hall, the bridge between Hampden and City Hall. I am simply tired of failed policies that do not focus on building relationships in the community to confront real-world issues such as: food desserts, job creation and economic development, affordable housing opportunities, safe communities, reduction of incarceration and violence rates, combating drug addiction. I see the possibility of the 7th District because the people who live in the community are some of the best people that you will find, they are working every day to move their communities forward and they are tired of failed promises and want someone that will be a part of the community and someone they can relate to and trust. The list of negatives from others can trail on yet I see beauty in the 7th District and that is why I am Fighting Downtown for A Better Uptown!</p>",
    "q2":"1- Safe communities- I plan to address this issue by: 1- looking at gun violence and accessing the City's data which will allow us to make better informed decisions about the way we target violent offenders. 2- Reach the youth and work on violence prevention as well as provide job readiness and training programs that offer other opportunities for the youth. 3- Change the relationship between the police and the community to make it one of mutual respect and one that thrives on the relationships that are formed opposed to the authority. 2- Job training and development- I will work require all developers to sign PMA's that will require them offer jobs to members of the community, in addition, I will partner with small and large businesses so that I can learn exactly what skills are needed that the residents can learn and work to offer those skills in job training and job readiness centers. Furthermore, I will insist that we hold job training facilities accountable to the people who enroll in their programs so that we can insure that any person who goes to a job readiness program is equipped to work and can find a job that can be a career opportunity. 3- Transportation- In West Baltimore we do not have a reliable means of transportation. I will work to implement a transportation system that allows the residents to get to and from work quickly, safely, and effectively.</p>",
    "q3":"The lessons I have drawn from the death of Freddie Gray and the subsequent protests and unrest are: 1- Freddie Gray was a human being but he was not treated as such and that in itself is a grave injustice. 2- We cannot judge the many for the actions of the few- I saw the beauty of individuals coming together to not only demand justice for Freddie Gray but to evolve into a new era in Baltimore. 3- Hate begets more hate- the opposite is also true, love begets more love so when work in the spirit of brotherly love we are able to not only protest but to create transformation. 4- The protests and unrest had an underlying effect; the untimely death of Freddie Gray ignited many of the issues that residents of Baltimore have faced: generational and systematic poverty, police brutality and lack of positive relationships between the community and the police, lack of government accountability and transparency- we have to hold our elected officials accountable to the community as well as to addressing not only these issues but so many others that have gone unresolved for decades. 4- Change and unity are possible- the great news is that we have the power to elect leaders that are committed to unity, accountability, social justice, and providing the opportunity for every person to have an opportunity to succeed.</p>",
    "q4":"Baltimore should reduce it's property tax rate, currently, Baltimore has one of the highest property tax rates in Maryland. To reduce the property tax rate, we have to use the additional income that Baltimore has earned as a result of increased property values. In many areas of the City, property values have increased and therefore the amount of revenue that the City has earned is higher which offers the opportunity for using the added income to reduce the property taxes. I do not agree with the use of tax increment financing in lieu of taxes and other incentives to encourage developers; I would overall work to reduce commercial property taxes but tax increment financing(TIF) does not overall benefit the City. When the City engages in a TIF agreement, the benefits are for the developer. If it is not explicitly stated that the developer will hire people from the community, work with job readiness programs to insure that qualified applicants are being given competitive jobs, as well as insuring that the developer will be a benefit to the community then a TIF should not be used because in the end the City could be left with the bill that the developer would have traditionally paid such as those used for roads. In the event that a TIF is used it must be combined with an agreement that will serve the community; the TIF cannot stand alone to offer incentives to the developer without the developer offering tangible rewards to the citizens.</p>",
    "q5":"In order to encourage commercial and residential revitalization of neighborhoods we have to take a multi-dimensional approach. At FEMINC I have changed blight by taken abandoned buildings and created a resource center for the community; changing blight is a community effort. We cannot do as Governor Hogan has done, and say, we will invest to tear down properties yet we have not worked with residents and activists that have lived in Baltimore. In order to revitalize commercial and residential neighborhoods, the same amount of disinvestment that has went into our communities have to now be changed to reinvest. Many ask me, what would I have done with the money that the Governor is proposing to \"redevelop\" Baltimore- I can clearly answer- the money would have went to job training programs, developing green spaces so that in West Baltimore we can have parks, fresh food gardens and markets, and provide grants to those organizations and community associations that have already been doing the work of advocating for West Baltimore communities. The Vacants to Value program has not been successful in my opinion; the intended mission of the program was to redevelop blighted areas. Unfortunately, I have not seen this happen in West Baltimore where we still have many vacant homes. In addition, many developers have began redevelopment and ended the projects early, many individuals are unable to receive financing to purchase the homes, and once areas are redeveloped the homes are selling for $300,000 which is an open door for gentrification.</p>",
    "q6":"The chief barrier to economic development and job creation in Baltimore is there is a disconnect between employers and potential employees. In order to bridge this divide we have not only invest in small businesses that traditionally hire locally, we also have to work with larger companies to insure that anyone who wants a job in Baltimore is trained for the job they want. We have to build a bridge between employers and trade schools to be sure that the job training that we offer is in demand in the job market. In addition, we have to look at those citizens who have not been a part of the job market traditionally and get them to work; the individuals who have been unable to find employment based on educational barriers or background barriers- these individuals have to be included in the job market. Essentially, Baltimore has a diverse economy with the potential to offer every citizen who wants a job the opportunity to work and that starts by working with small business owners, large business, vocational and trade schools to create partnership that benefits residents in the 7th District and throughout Baltimore.</p>",
    "q7":"The current balance between the mayor and City Council is not appropriate; currently the City Council needs more votes than the Congress and the General Assembly to overrides vetoes issued by the Mayor. The Mayor has recently vetoed several of the City Council bills. I would agree with the amendments that the current City Council is proposing to reduce the power of the Mayor such as: reducing the amount of votes necessary to override a veto as well as reducing the size of the Board of Estimates. Currently, members serving on the Board of Estimates report to the Mayor; this is an unfair practice and still gives the Mayor control of the Board- those who serve on the Board should be separately elected. The balance of power between the Mayor and City Council should be able to provide the opportunity to be checked on both sides of the spectrum. The City Council has to have the power to affect change in the Districts that they represent which will be better for not only individual Districts but for the entire City.</p>",
    "q8":"The most important issue the City Council has dealt with in the last four years include: 1- the current debate to provide funding to the youth of Baltimore that will expand youth services, 2- \"Ban the Box\" bill which allowed ex-offenders assistance with finding jobs, and 3- implementing body cameras for all police officers to assist with police accountability. While the Council has tackled some issues, there are many issues that still need to be resolved. These include developing real plans for changing blight in our communities that redevelop communities without displacing members of the community, plans that include funds for job training to reduce the likelihood of crimes taking place as well as reduce recidivism for ex-offenders, as well as plans that combat issues of the lack of access to quality food and efficient transportation. In fact, we have to move beyond plans to implementation that partners with the community instead of developing bills and then presenting them to the community. City Council members if they do not already need to have offices located in their Districts where residents can easily access them and the Council member is seen as a servant and a part of the community. In order to fully keep a pulse the issues that are taking place in the community as Councilman I would continue to be fully engaged and a part of the community and this will be the way to keep my focus on the right issues.</p>",
    "q9":"The weaknesses that I see in the delivery of city services is that in areas like the 7th District, city services are received last. For instance, as I have been knocking on doors and speaking to residents in the City I have heard numerous complaints regarding the timeliness of trash or snow removal. In addition, it is apparent that certain areas of the City receive services at a much more efficient rate than other areas. During our last snow storm you could easily go downtown and surrounding areas while areas in the 7th District were not shoveled at all. In order to improve response time and resident satisfaction the city has to work with residents in order to make their priorities a part of the plans that the city uses when developing the plans to deliver city services. When residents are a part of the planning and implementation process then we can improve resident satisfaction.</p>",
    "q10":"None- I am not a politician; the beauty of my candidacy is that I do not have political experience. As a Pastor, I know what it takes to empower not only our young people but to close the generational lines that divide us so that we may build strong communities. I have been an avid community leader and activist during the Freddie Gray protests but before that as well through: coaching young men's basketball teams, transforming blight in the community, as well as, standing up for social injustices.</p>"
  }
