    "facebook":"facebook.com/VoteDiamondK",
    "bio":"<p>Williams is “part of the administration” at Health Care Access Maryland and a former music executive, according to his campaign website. He did not respond to The Baltimore Sun’s candidate questionnaire.</p>",
    "q1":"Education is the most pressing issue facing my district! Now this is a huge thing, because I don't just mean the education of our children, I also mean job education and job training. Education on how to save money, the best ways to spend money and where to spend money. In our schools we need to utilize technology ie: laptops, tablets and USB Drives for all children, not textbooks that are bad for the environment and become outdated every four years. We need a focus on a modern education for our young people so we produce adults that can effectively compete in this ever changing marketplace. However, education does not end there, we also need to educate our young people living outside of the law and make sure that they know that there are better ways to provide for their families then criminal activity. Many of the people that are loitering, hanging out on street corners and committing crimes are really potential entrepreneurs who have become misguided and need direction. Through job education they could be trained to take whatever it is they're passionate about and create a business from that . Taking these measures will make them productive members of society not part of the problem.</p>",
    "q2":"Baltimore has not been pursing the right strategies to reduce violent crime because we are plagued with record shattering numbers. It is time to pivot and try some new ideas. There needs to be a focus on teaching conflict resolution and how to talk through disagreements. It is an absolute tragedy that our city's homicide rate was over 300 people in 2015. We must reverse this trend! I feel that our current Police Chief Kevin Davis has not been given a chance to prove what he can do because he has been in his office for less than a year, so it is too soon to judge him. However, he is responsible for the actions of his officers. We desperately improvement in police-community relations. In terms of diversity, we have to make sure our police officers look like the communities they serve and protect. They should reside in Baltimore and be held accountable for their actions, not protected for aggression. Baltimore Police should stop over policing our neighborhoods. We have to get to the point where children want to grow up and become police officers again. In order to do this they (children) have to feel like they are seeing 'Officer Friendly' - not an occupying military force. Yearly mental screenings should be conducted on all patrol officers to root out racist or overly aggressive people on the police force. Lethal force should be used as a last resort, not the first action!</p>",
    "q3":"The death of Freddie Gray shined a bright light on the need for the re-training of our police force. Luckily, Freddie Gray's arrest was caught on cell phone video, if not this case may have been swept under the rug completely. The protests and unrest are the result of Baltimore's frustration with police brutality, lack of opportunity, lack of resources and mistrust of the government.</p><p>I love the city of Baltimore, but if we continue to elect people with poor leadership qualities that don't take responsibility for their own mistakes, then things will continue to get worse. If we continue to have city council members that do not represent the people of the district: their wants, needs and their struggles, it's going to get worse!</p>",
    "q4":"Baltimore should reduce its property tax rate. We have one of the highest in the area. I understand why it is advantageous to develop a place like Harbor Point, but at the same time these type of TIF and PILOT for other areas around the city in desperate need of development.</p>",
    "q5":"Mayor Rawlings-Blake has made a commitment to grow the city by 10,000 families thru Vacants to Value but I don't think enough people know about this program. I do not think the incentives are as attractive as some other attempts at development. The recently announced Project C.O.R.E, or Creating Opportunities for Renewal and Enterprise, kicked off last month in the Sandtown-Winchester neighborhood. The goal here is to replace as many full blocks of blight as possible over the term of the project with green space that they hope will be more attractive to sell. They are reporting that 20 blocks will be done in the first year, so that remains to be seen. But I think we could do better and take it a step forward by actually building homes on the properties and truly lead by example. Instead of just knocking down the buildings and putting down a field why not erect a livable space focused on completing 10 blocks start to finish.</p>",
    "q6":"True opportunities for urban growth is what is hold economic development back. The scale are stacked too much in favor of people other than to poor. So we must balance the scales and focus more attention on developing small business.</p>",
    "q7":"Baltimore has one of the strongest Mayoral systems in the country. If you have a visionary in office - this is an inspiring thing but if the Mayor lacks vision, the power they possess can be frustrating for the City Council. The requirement for a three-fourths legislative vote to override an executive veto is too high and very rarely achieved and should be lowered.</p>",
    "q8":"The City Council has touched some important issues like Baltimore Police wearing body cameras, the confirmation of Police Chief Kevin Davis and the plan to sell four city-owned parking garages to raise money for improvements to recreation centers and pools. However they is still more work to do.</p>",
    "q9":"The handling of snow emergencies, snow removal etc is something which we need to improve on. Trash removal is another area that improvement is needed in. 2 trash days per week and a more concrete mandatory recycling system should be put into place to help reduce rodents. The citizens of the city need a direct line of communication that can help with reporting service needs etc.</p>",
    "q10":"I am running for office to knock down the barriers that are holding my community back. For the last 20 years, things have become progressively worse. The 8th District needs a Councilman that can effectively engage young people to become involved in the political process, because they are our future - but at the same time, effectively addressing the needs of seniors and other adults in the community. After the uprising of 2015, we can no longer stand on the side-lines and assume the same old politics as usual have our best interests at heart!</p>"
