    "q1":"Jobs:  I'll encourage developers and fellow colleagues on the council to respect the rule of reciprocity. The rule of reciprocity simply states that; if developers are going to do business in Baltimore City, they must be willing to train and hire local residents in my district. I'll champion the use of high‐road contractors that support good apprenticeship programs, job slots and pre‐apprenticeship training for local residents while implementing a comprehensive pre‐apprenticeship program.</p><p>Public Safety: ​I will reduce crime with strategies of prevention, intervention, suppression and collaboration. Crime is a major problem across our city, but crime is an bi-product of deeper issues--education and economics. As your councilman, I will strengthen the bonds between the community and the police department, focusing on community policing to tackle the distrust between citizen and police. This will help lower our crime rate.</p><p>Affordable Housing: We need rent control as an immediate step to address the crisis of out-of-control, unaffordable rent. Too many of our citizens pay too much money to live in deplorable conditions. Meanwhile, out of state landlords and developers get rich by raising rents, but not fixing properties. The city council should immediately pass a resolution demanding the state government remove the ban on rent control, and bring a legal challenge to it. Also code enforcement should be given the proper resources to find and hold slumlords responsible.</p>",
    "q2":"I have all the confidence in out police department and the leadership. However, the police strategy needs to change from a fighting strategy to a protect and serve strategy.</p>",
