    "bio":"<p>Williams, serves on the boards of Civic Works, the Coldstream Homestead Montebello Community Corp. and the Real Food Farm. He has not previously held elected office. Williams holds an MBA from Southern New Hampshire University.</p>",
    "q1":"The most pressing issues are community redevelopment, crime and affordable housing. To combat crime, I would advocate for more community based police officers. There has been a lot of distrust with the police department, so citizens are less likely to tell them if they know of a crime that has been committed. I would also advocate for stronger witness protection. For citizens to come forward with information, they have to feel safe. Since Baltimore is city of neighborhoods, there redevelopment is key to the rebuilding of the city. Certain neighborhoods have been forgotten and look like third world country's. We need to bring small and local businesses back to our neighborhoods. This can create job growth and reinvestment back into the communities. Great schools and affordable housing will bring new citizens into our existing great neighborhoods. Affordable housing is an issue for many of the residents in my district. In my neighborhood, Coldstream Homestead Montebello, many of the residents are stuck paying high rent for substandard housing. To combat, I will limited the number outside developer rental units in impoverished neighborhoods. I would attract developers to create affordable homes for purchase. I would create mix use developments where there is a mix of rental units and units for purchase.</p>",
    "q2":"",
    "q3":"With the unrest in the city, we learned our citizens are fed up with business as usual. We learned that we can no longer take our citizens for granted. We learned that the residents of the city are looking for a hand up and not a hand out. Even though the unrest destroyed certain areas of the city, it also brought the residents closer together. I witnessed this first hand while on the scene at Penn North the day after the unrest. Citizens from all over the city was on the scene to cleanup in the aftermath of the unrest. The death of Freddie Gray exposed some of the weaknesses in some of the current police procedures and policies. His death placed a national spotlight on the issue of police brutality and the use of excessive force. From this we learned that the citizens of Baltimore will no longer stand by and let the concerns go unanswered and unaddressed.</p>",
    "q4":"Yes, the property tax rate for home owners should be reduced in Baltimore. One way to achieve this is to reduce the amount of property tax breaks that are giving to large businesses. A reduction in property taxes should not be the main selling point to attract developments such as Harbor Point.</p>",
    "q5":"Small and local businesses are the key to neighborhood revitalization. Small business is the key to bringing new investment, revenue and residents back to our communities. We need to make Baltimore a small business friendly city. To do this, we need to create incentives for small businesses. I would endorse and support incentives for hiring residents of the communities where these businesses will be located. The Vacants to Value program is a good to start to removing blight from our neighborhoods. I have seen first hand how this program, when used correctly, can eradicate urban blight. In the Coldstream Homestead Montebello neighborhood, the Vacants to Value program allowed us to eradicate an abandoned multi unit structure and an entire block of vacant and run down houses.</p>",
    "q6":"One of the chief barriers is opportunity. Before there is economic development and job creation, there has to be an opportunity for economic development and job creation. To create these opportunities, we have to attract these opportunities to our city. We need to highlight the fact that we are a sought after convention city and companies offering convention services can thrive in Baltimore. We need to highlight our proximity to an international airport and our proximity to the port and use this to attract opportunities to our city.</p>",
    "q7":"Baltimore is a mayor strong city. This means that the mayors share of power of the city is strong. I do believe that the balance of power is unbalanced. I would advocate to have the city council to have more control or more of a say in the operations of the city. One way I would change this is to change the structure of the Board of Estimates. With the mayor currently having three of the five votes of the board in unbalanced. With three votes, it is easier for the mayor to get funding for their priorities, which may or may not be the priorities of the council or the city.</p>",
    "q8":"I do believe the council has been focused on some of the right issues. Some of the issues that I believe the council has addressed in the correct manner of the last four year include, police body cameras, funding for youth programs, and the re-writing of our zoning code</p>",
    "q9":"The major weaknesses with the delivery of city services is communication and follow up. While I am out talking and listening to residents, many of them have issues when reporting issues to 311. The major issue they have is that many times their concerns are never addressed or there was no followup to their issue. The recent cleanup from the blizzard showed weaknesses in city services. Many residents were left in the dark as to when their streets were going to be cleaned. When asked of the street clearing map could be made public, the city's response was that is was not feasible. To improve the followup and communication, I would work with city agency directors to institute a time line for all service calls. Once the service is complete, A call or email would be sent to the resident to inform them that their issue has been addressed.</p>",
    "q10":"Baltimore City Council 14th District</p>"
