    "q1":"1) Crime and illegal drugs: In collaboration with the police department form a community task force with residents who are willing to be visible change agents in eradicating crime and drugs from each neighborhood. Identify hot spots and collect relevant information and allow police to target people, locations and activities one neighborhood at a time. I would pursue initiatives that decriminalize possession of some drugs for personal use. </p><p>2) Economic development, job creation and unemployment: Work with existing employers to identify low skilled jobs and develop employee readiness programs for local residents to fill these positions, once employed develop career pathways and training programs to facilitate advancement. Work with growing businesses who are creating new jobs to establish workforce development offerings that will invest in preparing our local workers for these new jobs in collaboration with local schools and colleges. </p><p>3) K-12 education: Public school reform is critical. Transforming the city/state partnership created in 1997 to reflect 21st century needs should be the starting point. This agreement outlines roles, responsibilities and oversight of K-12 which must vest more direct responsibility locally to ensure a critical eye is applied directly over the operations and management of school district resources by the school board (which should become partially elected) and other local elected officials and citizens. I will champion efforts to bring the community schools model to every city school. Community schools embed wrap-around programs and services in schools making them accessible to both the students and families.</p>",
    "q2":"No. Yes. I drafted legislation which was favorably approved by the 2015 general assembly and signed by Gov. Hogan in May 2015 to require an annual report from Baltimore Police Department on \"Community Policing\" outcomes. The first such report was released on January 1, 2016 and is available on the police department's website. Additionally, I wrote a course curriculum for the police academy for a 4-hour block of instruction that brought academy class #15-01 to a local school to engage directly with students, faculty and community leaders. This curriculum was approved by the prior police commissioner and is being adopted by the new, current commissioner for inclusion in upcoming academy classes. As president I will lead an initiative that brings the police together with neighborhood leaders to tear down barriers to cooperative community policing.</p>",
