    "q5":"Neighborhood revitalization must begin with inclusion of residents in the discussions, planning and development process. Small commercial and residential housing projects can quickly change the landscape of blighted neighborhoods. While incentives that provide tax breaks may be the most lucrative for developers other incentives that are less harmful to the municipal budget bottom-line (especially funding for schools) must be identified and implemented through laws and policies approved by the city council and as president I will champion those efforts. I will work with the city's Finance Board to effect the necessary changes in both law and policy in this matter. Partnerships with neighborhood community development corporations will empower residents and build their capacity to become leaders in revitalizing their neighborhoods. Vacants to Value generally is a failure. It has not produced the \"value\" of new affordable residential development and has chiefly produced new vacant land where houses use to stand. Governor Hogan's announcement while encouraging is also disappointing in that it did not include an option for neighborhoods to participate in the initiative, and it conveyed a lack of confidence in the local municipal government's ability to take a leadership role in the proposed efforts and instead vested the responsibility with a state agency the Maryland Stadium Authority.</p>",
    "q6":"Structural racism, low educational achievement, inadequate workforce readiness and substandard public transportation. The reality of the disparity that 2 separate and distinct Baltimores exist is a key barrier that must be eliminated. The social and economic disparities are often perpetuated by the actions of city government. Uptown vs downtown should only be destinations, but instead they represent divides in investments and opportunities. Redlining of opportunities and investments exists and government's role has to include ensuring those barriers are erased. It is widely perceived that government does nothing to change these dynamics and is a contributor as well. I will work with institutions, business, banks, mortgage companies, technology/communications businesses like Verizon to reverse these trends. Job creation is chiefly dependent on employers concluding that a ready workforce and favorably marketplace conditions exist in a specific location. Unfortunately Baltimore City no longer has a workforce sufficiently trained and skilled for many of the 21st century businesses that may be considering growth here. Improving educational outcomes for students attending our K-12 schools is a very high priority on my agenda. Additionally, our workforce pool includes many unemployed and displaced workers who have no viable re-training opportunities available. Investments in worker readiness and training must be made that truly turn the unemployed into productive employed citizens. I will work closely with the Mayor's Office of Employment Development to achieve these goals.</p>",
    "q7":"No. the balance of power is weighted heavily in favor of the mayor which limits the city council's ability to actively participate in governance and oversight of the city's business. Changes to the make up of the Board of Estimates is necessary to better align the balance of power between the office holders elected by the residents to govern and provide checks and balances over each of the other office holders. Additionally, the city council must be afforded opportunities to represent the citizens with voting membership on a number of municipal boards and commissions that govern critical city functions that serve citizens, like the hotel board and the finance board. I would seek to obtain the support of the entire council, to change the city charter to shift the balance of power accordingly and more equitably.</p>",
